"{\"uid\": \"si.com-olympics-what-to-watch-paris-olympics-august-3-kayak-cross-breakout-sport-biles-nedoroscik\", \"text\": \"It\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s Day 8 of the Olympics, and we\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099ve got a big one on tap. For many out there, you\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099ve now made it back to the safe refuge of the weekend and will have an easier time watching. (Could that be why the schedule makers chose Saturday and Sunday to give us the only two days in which track, swimming and gymnastics all overlap? Maybe!) My daily guide is once again here to help everyone know what to watch.  You can also subscribe toSports Illustrated\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s Daily Rings, my daily podcast where Dan Gartland and I go into significantly more detail on every sport every night. Our regular listeners were 100% ready for exciting moments in judo and trampoline Friday, and you still have time to join us for the rest of the Games. New episodes have been published every night before NBC\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s prime-time coverage is even over.  Here\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s what I\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099ll be watching Saturday, August 3.  This is not a comprehensive list;visit Olympics.comfor a full schedule. All events will stream live on Peacock. I\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099ll also be tweeting out a schedule of medal events, Team USA games and other favorites each day.  My Day 8 Olympics viewing guide!Track, swimming and gymnastics in one day. (And kayak cross!)#Paris2024pic.twitter.com/PQkO1NgOuh  Before we get to those typically marquee sports, I want to start out with something a little different. Kayak cross is a new event in the Olympics this year, and I think it\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s about to be a breakout hit.  You may have seen some canoe slalom races already at these Olympics\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094the events where canoes (or kayaks, they race both) are in the water with rapids and competitors are trying to paddle through and around gates as they take turns in a timed event. For the first time in an Olympics, we will now see multiple boats in the water at once, racing each other to the finish line.\\u00c2  Friday during the time trials, they were on the course solo. Saturday and Sunday we\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099ll get the real thing. Saturday will start with heats of three riders per race and the finals will have four in the water at the same time..  Did I mention the kayaks start out elevated above the course on a ramp that opens at the starting gate and dumps them into the water? Or that the riders have to do a barrel roll at some point during the race? Admit it: A part of you thinks I\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099m making this up as a prank. But truly, they have to dunk themselves, come back up for air and paddle to the finish line. I\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099m telling you; everyone will be talking about this over the weekend. So you should check it out.  Round 1 for the women starts at 9:30 a.m. ET, and the men will start at 10:40 a.m. ET. Team USA\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s Evy Leibfarth, who medaled earlier in these Olympics, has qualified in kayak cross as well.  The action on the track is heating up, and among the five medal events Saturday are a couple of big ones.  Let\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s start with the women\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s 100 meters, where Team USA\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s Sha\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099Carri Richardson is the favorite to win gold. She\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s been one of the faces of the U.S. delegation going into these Olympics, and this will be a huge moment for her.  In the shot put, AmericanRyan Crouser is going for his third straight Olympic gold, while his top competition may be fellow American Joe Kovacs \\u00e2\\u0080\\u00a6 who took silver to Crouser in Rio and Tokyo.  The other finals we\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099ll see are the women\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s triple jump, the 4X400 mixed relay (in which Team USAset a world record during the heats) and the men\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s decathlon. The full session of track and field starts at 1:35 p.m. ET.  With the team and individual all-arounds behind us, gymnastics will begin handing out medals on individual apparatuses. On Saturday we\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099ll see the living legend, America\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s favorite gymnast, an all-time great at their craft. Of course, I\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099m talking about pommel horse specialist Stephen Nedoroscik, who will try to follow up hismoment of glory in the team competitionwith an individual medal.  Oh right, we\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099ll see Simone Biles, too. She and Jade Carey will compete in the vault, beginning at 10:20 a.m. ET. Biles is already themost decorated gymnast in history, now a two-time Olympic all-around champion, and she\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099ll have a few more opportunities to add to her medal count.  Swimming is still going strong, and Saturday\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s 2:30 p.m. ET session includes four finals: the men\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s 100-meter fly, women\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s 200-meter IM, women\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s 800-meter free and the mixed 4X100 medley relay. The women\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s 800 will be another showdown between Katie Ledecky and Australia\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s Ariarne Titmus, which is must-see TV.  The U.S. women\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s soccer team has reached the win-or-go-home phase, and has a crucial quarterfinal against Japan at 9 a.m. ET. The team needs to win two more matches for a medal and three for a gold one.  Surfing has been delayed by poor weather, but the finals are finally scheduled to really, actually happen. They are slated for 3:24 p.m. ET, but check the schedule again Saturday just in case.  If you missed the experience of seeing French judo legendTeddy Riner compete in frontof his home crowd Friday, you\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099ll get another chance in the team event Saturday. France is the defending Olympic champion, which is how he got one of his six medals.\\u00c2  The U.S. women\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s 3x3 teamhas picked it up after a slow start. They will play against China at 1:05 p.m. ET and then possibly a second game depending on the result.  The U.S. men\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s five-on-five basketball team is also back in action, against Puerto Rico at 11:15 a.m. ET.  The U.S. men\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s water polo team has a crucial game against Montenegro, with both teams fighting to advance out of group play. That match gets underway at 10:35 a.m. ET.  Loading recommendations... Please wait while we load personalized content recommendations  Mitch Goldich is a senior editor for Sports Illustrated, mostly focused on the NFL. He has also covered the Olympics extensively and written on a variety of sports since joining SI in 2014. His work has been published by The New York Times, Baseball Prospectus and Food & Wine, among other outlets. Goldich has a bachelor\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s in journalism from Lehigh University and a master\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s in journalism from the Medill School at Northwestern University. He is a Philly native, now living in Boston, and he invented and popularized the octopus, when the same player scores a touchdown and the ensuing two-point conversion.  \\u00c2\\u00a9 2026ABG-SI LLC-SPORTS ILLUSTRATED IS A REGISTERED TRADEMARK OF ABG-SI LLC. - All Rights Reserved. The content on this site is for entertainment and educational purposes only. Betting and gambling content is intended for individuals 21+ and is based on individual commentators' opinions and not that of Sports Illustrated or its affiliates, licensees and related brands. All picks and predictions are suggestions only and not a guarantee of success or profit. If you or someone you know has a gambling problem, crisis counseling and referral services can be accessed by calling 1-800-GAMBLER.\"}"